Anonymous Mon 19 Sep 2022 01:20:16 No.51038192 Report
Quoted By: >>51038811
Been toying with a few ideas for having an extreme language barrier between humans and an anthro culture.
To dump a bit of backstory that may not come up in the text, they were revered by the Mayan cultures as gods, mostly because a few of them could produce miracles/magic. That time is long past.
If I used a logosyllabic script (like the Mayans), then I could assume that the Spanish never recognized it as separate from the human glyphs. They destroyed that, historically. But it also lets me make written Spanish the easiest way to communicate.
But it also puts an additional barrier between the two MCs. She would not stoop to learn the evil language and requires a translator, or a few. As I plan to have a very definite time limit on the plot, it means that I'll need to make big leaps so that they can manage anything without the translators. I also know that I don't want it to be one sided. By the story end, he knows a few handfuls of words & glyphs, barely baby talk but enough.
I'll probably make one of the translators a captured Indian, first by the Mission and then the anthros. It will be tough, but figuring out the body language should be easy. After that, all that's needed is the equivalent of one sentence.
